{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:54:16.899597", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic Report — RIP + WireGuard Mini-Internet\nDate: (current snapshot)\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall connectivity: The network is broadly healthy: hosts and servers can ping each other with low latency and no packet loss. HTTP requests over the WireGuard addresses succeed from host_1.\n- Primary abnormality: The \"web servers only accessible via VPN\" policy is not being enforced. The 20.0.0.0/24 web server LAN is being advertised into the interior via RIP and the web servers (and gateway) accept connections broadly. As a result both internal hosts (host_1 and host_2) can reach the web servers directly without needing the VPN overlay.\n- Localized likely root cause: Routing configuration on the external edge (external_router_1 and the gateway) is propagating the external 20.0.0.0/24 network into the internal RIP domain. In addition, the web servers and the VPN endpoint have permissive firewall policies and some WireGuard allowed-ips entries are broader than necessary — these factors together allow direct access.\n\nKey evidence gathered\n1) Reachability (ping) summary (selected results)\n- host_1 → web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4): 0% loss, RTT ~1.9 ms — successful\n- host_1 → vpn_server_1 (20.0.0.2): 0% loss — successful\n- host_2 → web_server_1_2, vpn_server_1: 0% loss — successful\n- web_server ↔ vpn_server: 0% loss — successful\nConclusion: IP reachability between internal hosts and external servers is intact and reliable.\n\n2) Router routes (FRR ip route snapshots)\n- gateway_router shows a RIP route: R>* 20.0.0.0/24 [120/2] via 192.168.0.6 on eth2 (i.e., gateway learned 20.0.0.0/24 via the external link).\n- external_router_1 shows 20.0.0.0/24 as directly connected (C>* 20.0.0.0/24).\n- Other routers (router1, router2) show 20.0.0.0/24 learned via next-hops through the RIP mesh.\nConclusion: The 20.0.0.0/24 prefix is being advertised and propagated across the RIP domain; internal routers know a route to the web servers' LAN.\n\n3) WireGuard state and behavior\n- vpn_server_1: wg0 present (172.16.1.1/24); peers configured for 172.16.1.11 and 172.16.1.22.\n- web_server_1_1: wg0 present (172.16.1.21); wg show shows an active handshake with vpn_server and some transferred bytes.\n- web_server_1_2: wg0 present (172.16.1.22); wg show shows an active handshake with vpn_server and some transferred bytes.\n- host_1: wg0 present (172.16.1.11); wg peer entry exists pointing to vpn_server (endpoint 20.0.0.2:51820). Host's wg show did not display a handshake line in the snapshot, though host_1 still successfully reached web servers via the 172.16.1.x addresses (curl succeeded).\nObservations:\n  - The VPN overlay itself appears functional between the VPN server and the web servers (handshakes and traffic observed).\n  - There is some inconsistency in the host_1 WireGuard snapshot (no handshake displayed in that particular snapshot, and initial wg interface counters were zero). Despite that, traffic to 172.16.1.22 from host_1 worked — likely a timing/snapshot artifact but worth noting.\n  - Some peers (on web servers) show allowed-ips or peer configurations that include the broader 172.16.1.0/24; mixing /24 and /32 allowed-ips across peers may have unintended routing behavior within the overlay.\n\n4) Application and firewall state on servers\n- web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2: Apache is listening on the WireGuard addresses (172.16.1.21:80 and 172.16.1.22:80).\n- iptables on vpn_server_1 and web servers show default ACCEPT policies (no restrictive firewall rules present in the snapshots).\nConclusion: No host-level filtering is preventing access to the web servers from other subnets.\n\nAnomalies and their localization\n1) Anomaly — Web servers accessible from internal network without VPN:\n   - Symptom: host_2 (10.0.1.2) can ping the web server and host_1 can directly connect to 172.16.1.22 and to 20.0.0.4.\n   - Localization: external_router_1 is directly connected to 20.0.0.0/24 and is advertising that network into RIP. gateway_router and internal routers have learned and are propagating 20.0.0.0/24.\n   - Evidence: FRR routing tables showing R>* 20.0.0.0/24 across routers; successful pings from internal hosts to web servers; permissive iptables on servers.\n\n2) Configuration inconsistency — WireGuard allowed-ips and peer state:\n   - Symptom: Mixed allowed-ips entries and inconsistent handshake visibility for host_1.\n   - Localization: WireGuard configs on host_1, vpn_server_1, and web servers.\n   - Evidence: wg show outputs show peers with allowed-ips varying between /32 and /24; host_1 wg show lacked a handshake timestamp in the captured output even though connectivity exists (possible timing artifact). Web servers show active handshakes with vpn_server.\n\n3) (Minor) Router RIP metrics vary — expected in a multi-hop mesh:\n   - Symptom: Different metric/hop counts for same prefixes across routers (e.g., 20.0.0.0/24 advertised with metric 2 on some routers, 3 on others).\n   - Localization: normal behavior for RIP in a multi-hop topology; no evidence of convergence problems in the provided snapshots/time window.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\n- The intended isolation of the external web LAN (20.0.0.0/24) to \"VPN-only\" access is not in effect because the external-router/gateway are advertising the web LAN via RIP into the internal routing domain. Internal routers and hosts therefore have a routing path to 20.0.0.0/24 independent of the WireGuard overlay.\n- Contributing factors:\n  - The web servers and VPN endpoint have permissive firewall rules (ACCEPT), so once routing exists, nothing blocks access.\n  - WireGuard peer configurations show some broad allowed-ips settings (172.16.1.0/24 on some peers) which could enable intra-overlay routing patterns that are broader than intended.\n- Result: Internal hosts can directly reach web servers over the infrastructure, bypassing the intended VPN-only requirement.\n\nImpact\n- Policy/segmentation breach: The web servers that were intended to be reachable only via the VPN are reachable from the internal network.\n- Confidentiality/segmentation: Any host on the internal RIP domain (e.g., host_2) can reach web servers without going through the overlay controls.\n- Operational: Otherwise, connectivity and application responsiveness appear good (low latency, no packet loss).\n\nConfidence and notes\n- Confidence: High that the 20.0.0.0/24 prefix is being propagated via RIP (FRR route table evidence) and that firewall policies are permissive (iptables output). High that this propagation is the reason web servers are reachable without VPN.\n- The minor inconsistency in host_1 WireGuard snapshot (missing handshake timestamp despite successful traffic) could be a timing/snapshot artifact; traffic tests confirm reachability over the overlay addresses.\n\nRelevant outputs referenced (summary)\n- Global reachability results: pings successful between hosts and servers; curl from host_1 to http://172.16.1.22/ returned quickly.\n- FRR routing tables: 20.0.0.0/24 present as C on external_router_1 and as R on gateway_router and others.\n- wg show / ip addr snapshots: wg0 interfaces present on vpn_server_1 and web servers and host_1; active handshakes observed between vpn_server and web servers; host_1 had wg config but handshake visibility varied in snapshots.\n- iptables: all show ACCEPT policy in chains (no blocking rules present).\n\nEnd of report.\n\n(If you want, I can now collect specific FRR configuration snippets from external_router_1 and gateway_router, or show the exact wg configuration files and RIP interfaces to further pinpoint the configuration lines causing the advertisement.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10767, "output_tokens": 5948, "total_tokens": 16715, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9856}, "output_token